query:
title: Is there any simplified way to create several operation for one specific resource?

question: I have one specific resource with URL path: /configurations/event-hub
That means event-hub is one specific resource under configurations.
Currently, I write code like below, and does anyone can help review to see if I can refactor my code with any other simplified way? Because all the 4 operations are based on the same route: /configurations/event-hub, and they are the PUT/GET/DELETE/POST action for the same resource.
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@doc("Create or replace EventHub configuration.")
@route("/configurations/event-hub")
@put
op createOrReplaceEventHubConfig(
@doc("API version parameter")
@query("api-version") apiVersion: string,
@doc("EventHub configuration.")
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@body body: EventHubConfig
): {
@statusCode status: 200;
@doc("EventHub configuration.")
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@body body: EventHubConfig;
};
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@doc("Get EventHub configuration.")
@route("/configurations/event-hub")
@get
op getEventHubConfig(
@doc("API version parameter")
@query("api-version") apiVersion: string,
): {
@statusCode status: 200 | 404;
@doc("EventHub configuration.")
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@body body: EventHubConfig;
};
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@doc("Delete EventHub configuration.")
@route("/configurations/event-hub")
@delete
op deleteEventHubConfig(
@doc("API version parameter")
@query("api-version") apiVersion: string,
): {
@statusCode status: 204;
};
@added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
@doc("Send ping to EventHub to verify configuration.")
@route("/configurations/event-hub:ping")
@post
op pingEventHub(
@doc("API version parameter")
@query("api-version") apiVersion: string,
): {
@statusCode status: 200;
};

response:
You can simplify your code by grouping operations under a namespace using the `@route` decorator. This approach allows you to define all operations for the same resource in a single namespace, reducing redundancy and improving readability. Here's an example:

```typespec
@route("/configurations/event-hub")
namespace EventHubConfig {
  @added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
  @doc("Create or replace EventHub configuration.")
  @put
  op createOrReplace(
    @query("api-version") apiVersion: string,
    @body body: EventHubConfig
  ): {
    @statusCode status: 200;
    @body body: EventHubConfig;
  };

  @added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
  @doc("Get EventHub configuration.")
  @get
  op get(
    @query("api-version") apiVersion: string
  ): {
    @statusCode status: 200 | 404;
    @body body: EventHubConfig;
  };

  @added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
  @doc("Delete EventHub configuration.")
  @delete
  op delete(
    @query("api-version") apiVersion: string
  ): {
    @statusCode status: 204;
  };
}

@route("/configurations/event-hub:ping")
namespace EventHubPing {
  @added(ApiVersions.v2025_05_20)
  @doc("Send ping to EventHub to verify configuration.")
  @post
  op ping(
    @query("api-version") apiVersion: string
  ): {
    @statusCode status: 200;
  };
}
```

This approach groups operations logically under namespaces, making the code easier to maintain and understand. The `@route` decorator ensures that all operations within the namespace share the same base path.

To override the `contentType` for a PATCH operation in TypeSpec, you can use the `@header` decorator to explicitly specify the `contentType` header for the operation. This approach allows you to maintain compatibility with the existing API behavior while leveraging TypeSpec's traits and decorators. Here's an example:

```typespec
@patch
op updateResource(
  @header contentType: "application/json",
  @body resource: Partial<Resource>
): Resource;
```

This ensures that the `contentType` is explicitly set to `application/json` for the PATCH operation. If you need to handle multiple content types, you can specify them as a union:

```typespec
@patch
op updateResource(
  @header contentType: "application/json" | "application/merge-patch+json",
  @body resource: Partial<Resource>
): Resource;
```

This approach is straightforward and aligns with TypeSpec's best practices for specifying content types. If you have already implemented a custom function, this method provides a simpler alternative without requiring additional customization.

