To make an interface internal in TypeSpec so that it does not appear in the public interface of the Python SDK, you can use the `@access` decorator with the value `"internal"`. This will mark the interface and its operations as internal, ensuring they are hidden from the public interface.

Here is an example:

```typespec
import "@azure-tools/typespec-client-generator-core";

using Azure.ClientGenerator.Core;

@@access(Contoso.WidgetManager.Widgets, "internal");
```

This approach ensures that the interface `Widgets` and its operations are marked as internal, preventing them from being exposed in the public SDK interface. Note that Python does not change behavior based on `protocolAPI` or `convenientAPI`, but marking the interface as internal will still hide it from direct imports and usage.

